## Core Licensure & Operational Depth

### The Operational Baseline (TCEQ Class A)
My professional foundation is built on over two decades of dedicated service in municipal water and wastewater utilities. I hold an active **Class A Water Treatment Operator license** issued by the Texas Commission on Environmental Quality (TCEQ).

*Customer Service Inspector (CSI):** Officially licensed to perform high-level system inspections, ensuring complete compliance with cross-connection control, backflow prevention, and public health regulations.

* **What It Means:** A Class A license is the highest level of environmental licensure recognized by the State of Texas. Achieving it requires a minimum of 8 years of direct field experience, hundreds of hours of specialized engineering and utility coursework, and passing comprehensive state board examinations.
* **The Security Impact:** This background provides an unshakeable, real-world understanding of complex physical process loops, industrial hydraulics, chemical safety, and the practical constraints that govern plant floor operations. It ensures security solutions fit the reality of the plant floor.

### The Cybersecurity Layer
To complement my field experience, I have systematically cross-trained into cyber defense. This allows me to act as a highly effective "translator layer" between technical security analysts and boots-on-the-ground industrial operators.

* **Core Validations:** Documented foundational proficiency via industry-recognized standards, including CompTIA Security+ ce and the ISC2 Certified in Cybersecurity (CC) designations.
* **OT/ICS Specialization:** Advanced industrial architecture, threat analysis, and infrastructure defense training provided by the Cybersecurity and Infrastructure Security Agency (CISA), Idaho National Laboratory (the 210W curriculum), and the Dragos Academy.

